subSection.paragraph:
External morphology and measurements. The specimens studied (and their tissue samples) were deposited at the Museo de Historia Natural La Salle ( MHNLS ), Caracas, Venezuela . For comparisons with all other species of
Pseudogonatodes
, we examined museum specimens available at MHNLS , Museu Paraense Emílio Goeldi, Belém, Brazil (MPEG), and at Leibniz Institute for the Analysis of Biodiversity Change, Museum Koenig, Bonn, Germany (LIB) (Appendix 1), as well as literature on morphological descriptions and redescriptions ( Ruthven 1915 ; Noble 1921 ; Parker 1926 , 1935 ; Roux 1927 ; Vanzolini 1967 ; Huey & Dixon 1970 ; Hoogmoed 1973 ; Avila-Pires 1995 ; Avila-Pires & Hoogmoed 2000 ;
Esqueda et al . 2016
;
Montes-Correa et al . 2021
). Sex and maturity were determined by dissection and direct inspection of gonads ( i.e. , presence and development of testes or ovaries, convolute oviducts, and oviductal eggs) in most of the larger specimens.For those non-dissected ( e.g. , the holotype ), maturity was verified from complete bone mineralization through x-ray computed microtomography images, while sex was determined by inspection of tail base condition ( i.e. , bulged on the ventral surface immediately posterior to cloaca in males; not bulged in females). We largely follow Avila-Pires (1995) and Avila-Pires & Hoogmoed (2000) for morphological description format, pholidotic nomenclature, and scale counts. Scale counts and morphometric measurements were performed by the first author under a stereomicroscope; bilateral meristic and qualitative characters were recorded from both sides and are presented as right/left. Morphometric measurements were taken with a caliper to the nearest 0.1 mm , except for limbs and tail which were measured with a piece of string and a ruler. We recorded a total of 10 morphometric measurements and 23 scale counts as follows: Measurements: snout-vent length ( SVL ), from tip of snout to anterior margin of vent; axilla-groin distance (AGD), from posterior border of arm insertion to anterior border of leg insertion; tail length (TL), from anterior margin of vent to tail tip; head length (HL), from tip of snout to posterior margin of tympanum; head width (HW), at maximum head width; head depth (HD), at the maximum head depth; eye-to-nares distance (EN), from center of naris to anterior border of orbit; snout length (SL), from tip of snout to anterior border of orbit; forelimb length (FLL), from axilla to tip of 3 rd finger; hind limb length (HLL), from groin to tip of 4 th toe. Scale counts: postrostrals (PR), in a transverse line juxtaposed to the posterodorsal margin of rostral; postnasals (PN), the scales posteriorly juxtaposed to the nasal; loreals (L), between postnasals and anterior border of orbit; scales in a transverse row between the 1 st and 2 nd supralabials suture of each side (SBSL); supralabials (SL); infralabials (IL); supraciliaries (SC), enlarged and flattened scales aligned on anterior and upper margin of eye forming a supraciliary flap; postmentals (PM), enlarged scales on chin juxtaposed along the posterior margin of mental; ventral scales along a midventral row, between throat and anterior border of cloaca (VMR-a), from anterior level of arms to anterior border of cloaca (VMR-b), and between anterior levels of forelimbs and hind limbs (VMR-c); scales around midbody ( SAM ); ventrals in a transverse row at midbody (VTM); lamellae under 1 st to 5 th finger (LFI, LFII, LFIII, LFIV , and LFV, respectively) and, lamellae under 1 st to 5 th toe (LTI, LTII, LTIII, LTIV , and LTV, respectively). As indicated by Avila-Pires & Hoogmoed (2000) , the third lamella under the 4 th toe was counted from the tip of the toe toward the sole of the foot. We follow Avila-Pires (1995) for coding the pattern of subcaudal scales, where each enlarged midventral scale is represented by an Arabic number (1 for single scales and 2 for paired scales) and the number of small scales laterodistally in contact with these is denoted by single or double apostrophe (for one or two small scales, respectively).

subSubSection.paragraph:
Mental scale large, U-shaped, posterior margin deeply concave, without posterior clefts. Postmentals five, polygonal, about twice the size of adjacent scales on chin, aligned forming an arc along the posterior margin of mental; the three medial postmentals nearly rounded, the two most lateral postmentals roughly rectangular. Anteriormost scales of chin nearly flat, polygonal (almost rounded), juxtaposed, gradually changing into slightly smaller granules toward center of throat; noticeably larger, flatter, and elongate those scales of chin in contact with or near to infralabials (
Fig. 3D
). Infralabials 5/5, the first much larger, 2.6–2.7 times as wide as the second; first infralabial reaching (left side) or surpassing (right side) anterior border of orbit; suture between third and fourth infralabials below center of eye (
Fig. 3B–C
). Scales on dorsal and lateral surfaces of neck granular, slightly larger than those on top of head and similar in size to dorsal body scales. Anterior scales of throat small, granular, juxtaposed; progressively larger towards the posterior throat edge, with a short transitional area at the mid-throat level; scales on posterior half of throat large, cycloid, imbricate, similar to those on ventral body surface.

Dorsal scales of body granular (
Fig. 2A
), slightly larger than scales on top of head; granules on vertebral area conical, erected, juxtaposed, somewhat misaligned; granules on dorsolateral surfaces and flanks barely larger than vertebrals, juxtaposed, arranged in diagonal rows, subtly flattened anterodorsally and slightly tilted posteriorly. A narrow lateral transitional zone between dorsals and ventrals. Ventral scales distinctly larger, distally rounded to ovate, flat, smooth, imbricate, arranged in both longitudinal and oblique rows (
Fig. 2B
); 91 scales around midbody, 22 of which are ventrals; 27 scales in a midventral row between anterior levels of fore- and hind limbs, 33 until border of cloaca, 40 between first enlarged ventral on throat to cloaca; anterior margin of cloaca bordered by one to two rows of minute scales. First 10–12 rows of dorsal scales at tail base (about five rows on lateral surfaces) similar in shape and size to dorsal body scales, followed by a short transitional area (about 4–5 scale rows) and then by large, flat, smooth, imbricate scales, similar to those on belly. A midventral row of slightly enlarged, roughly hexagonal caudal scales, starting about 5–6 scales from posterior margin of cloaca (not regenerated tail), alternately in contact latero-posteriorly with one or two smaller scales in a 1’1” pattern (
Fig. 4C
); enlarged midventral scales in latero-posterior contact with two scales (
i.e.
, 1”) larger than those in contact with a single scale (1’).

Along the inner wall of the supraoccipital, prootics, and otooccipitals are large, well-developed endolymphatic sacs that project slightly posteriorly and distinctly anteriorly beyond the supraoccipital. Anteriorly, they extend along the posterior third of the parietals and are in close contact with them dorsally (
Figs. 6‒8
). Endolymphatic sacs are also present in MHNLS 22711 but absent in MHNLS 22712. A small posteromedial gap between the parietal and the medial border of the supraoccipital is present in MHNLS 22711 (
Fig. 11E
) and MHNLS 22712 (
Fig. 11J
), but it is missing in MHNLS 21643 (
Fig. 6B
), where both bones are in firm contact. In MHNLS 22711 the gap is filled by the endolymphatic sacs.

